   "source": [
    "# check target class\n",
    "print(dataset[\"target\"].unique())"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "a15c49e8",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Convert target to binary\n",
    "dataset[\"target\"] = (dataset[\"target\"] > 0).astype(int)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "id": "cf6548f5",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# SPLIT FEATURES AND TARGET\n",
    "X = dataset.drop(\"target\", axis=1)\n",
    "y = dataset[\"target\"]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "id": "1eba5a05",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn.impute import SimpleImputer\n",
    "\n",
    "#  clean names columns\n",
    "X.columns = X.columns.str.lower()\n",
    "\n",
    "# numeric conversion and imputation\n",
    "num_cols = [\"age\", \"trestbps\", \"chol\", \"thalach\", \"oldpeak\", \"ca\"]\n",
    "\n",
    "# Convert to numeric\n",
    "X[num_cols] = X[num_cols].apply(pd.to_numeric, errors='coerce')\n",
    "\n",
    "# Impute missing values\n",
    "imputer = SimpleImputer(strategy= \"median\")\n",
    "X[num_cols] = imputer.fit_transform(X[num_cols])\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "31626bd3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 2- Encode categorical features\n",
    "\n",
    "Although several variables were stored as numeric types, such as **(`sex`, `cp`[chest pain], `fbs`[fasting blood sugar], `restcg`, `examg`, `slope`, `thal`)**. These variable were therefore treated as categorical and encoded using-hot enconding to avoid introducing artificial ordinal relationship.\n",
    "\n",
    "We used [get.dummies()](https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/reference/api/pandas.get_dummies.html) to convert categorical variable into dummy/indicator varianle"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "2dd54e4a",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Identify category variables\n",
    "cat_cols = [\"sex\", \"cp\", \"fbs\", \"restecg\", \"exang\", \"slope\", \"thal\"]\n",
    "\n",
    "# Apply encoding\n",
    "X_encoded = pd.get_dummies(X, columns=cat_cols, drop_first=True)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Convert ALL to numeric (IMPORTANT)\n",
    "X_encoded = X_encoded.astype(float)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "5a295553",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "After encoding the dataset contained 18 features, including both numerical variables and one-hot encoded categorical variable."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f40c3ca5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 3- Feature Scaling and Standardization"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "72747d81",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Standardization was applied using the `StandardScaler` from `sklearn`. This method subtract the mean and divides by standard deviation for each feature, resulting in variable with zero mean and unit variance"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "id": "060a6586",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Means: [5.44389439e+01 1.31689769e+02 2.46693069e+02 1.49607261e+02\n",
      " 1.03960396e+00 6.63366337e-01 6.79867987e-01 1.65016502e-01\n",
      " 2.83828383e-01 4.75247525e-01 1.48514851e-01 1.32013201e-02\n",
      " 4.88448845e-01 3.26732673e-01 4.62046205e-01 6.93069307e-02\n",
      " 5.94059406e-02 3.86138614e-01]\n",
      "Variances: [8.14277903e+01 3.08728839e+02 2.67200150e+03 5.21538825e+02\n",
      " 1.34364605e+00 8.70176127e-01 2.17647507e-01 1.37786056e-01\n",
      " 2.03269832e-01 2.49387315e-01 1.26458190e-01 1.30270453e-02\n",
      " 2.49866571e-01 2.19978433e-01 2.48559509e-01 6.45034801e-02\n",
      " 5.58768748e-02 2.37035585e-01]\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "scaler = StandardScaler()\n",
    "X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_encoded)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Means:\", scaler.mean_)\n",
    "print(\"Variances:\", scaler.var_)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "6341310d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The computer **means and variances** show substantial differences in the scale of the variables, with some features exhibiting significantly larger variability than others. This imbalance would bias distance-based methods such as PCA. Therefore, standardization was applied to normalize all features to a common scale, ensuring that no single variable dominates the analysis."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "03d7cf26",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Step A: Principal Component Analysis"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "id": "9a4f5647",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "[0.18995818 0.09332318 0.08128874 0.07471348 0.07281696 0.06712585\n",
      " 0.05742977 0.0503162  0.04825454 0.0451006  0.04313879 0.03957069\n",
      " 0.03807293 0.03102809 0.02313375 0.02220122 0.01657576 0.00595127]\n",
      "[0.18995818 0.28328136 0.3645701  0.43928358 0.51210054 0.57922639\n",
      " 0.63665616 0.68697236 0.7352269  0.7803275  0.82346629 0.86303698\n",
      " 0.9011099  0.932138   0.95527175 0.97747297 0.99404873 1.        ]\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn.decomposition import PCA\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "\n",
    "pca = PCA()\n",
    "X_pca = pca.fit_transform(X_scaled)\n",
    "\n",
    "explained = pca.explained_variance_ratio_\n",
    "cumulative = np.cumsum(explained)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(explained)\n",
    "print(cumulative)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
